# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: purescript
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] In computer programming, especially in functional programming and type theory, an **algebraic data type** (**ADT**) is a composite data type, i.e. a type formed by combining other types.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] An algebraic data type is defined by two key constructions: a *sum* and a *product*.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] These are sometimes referred to as "OR" and "AND" types.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] A **sum type** is a choice between possibilities.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The value of a sum type can match one of several defined *variants*.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] For example, a type representing the state of a traffic light could be either `Red`, `Amber`, or `Green`.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] A shape type could be either a `Circle` (which stores a radius) *or* a `Square` (which stores a width).
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] In formal terms, these variants are known as tagged unions or disjoint unions.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Each variant has a name, called a **constructor**, which can also carry data.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Enumerated types are a simple form of sum type where the constructors carry no data.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] A **product type** combines types together.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] A value of a product type will contain a value for each of its component types.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] For example, a `Point` type might be defined to contain an `x` coordinate (an integer) *and* a `y` coordinate (also an integer).
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Formal examples of product types include tuples and records.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The set of all possible values of a product type is the Cartesian product of the sets of its component types.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Values of algebraic data types are typically handled using pattern matching.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] This feature allows a programmer to check which constructor a value was made with and extract the data it contains in a convenient and type-safe way.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data types were introduced in Hope, a small functional programming language developed in the 1970s at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] One of the most common examples of an algebraic data type is the singly linked list.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] A list type is a sum type with two variants, `Nil` for an empty list and `Cons *x* *xs*` for the combination of a new element *x* with a list *xs* to create a new list.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] `Cons` is an abbreviation of *cons*truct.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Many languages have special syntax for lists defined in this way.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] For example, Haskell and ML use `[]` for `Nil`, `:` or `::` for `Cons`, respectively, and square brackets for entire lists.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Here, `Empty` represents an empty tree, `Leaf` represents a leaf node, and `Node` organizes the data into branches.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] In most languages that support algebraic data types, it is possible to define parametric types.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Examples are given later in this article.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Somewhat similar to a function, a data constructor is applied to arguments of an appropriate type, yielding an instance of the data type to which the type constructor belongs.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] For example, the data constructor `Leaf` is logically a function `Int -> Tree`, meaning that giving an integer as an argument to `Leaf` produces a value of the type `Tree`.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] As `Node` takes two arguments of the type `Tree` itself, the datatype is recursive.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Operations on algebraic data types can be defined by using pattern matching to retrieve the arguments.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Thus, a `Tree` given to `depth` can be constructed using any of `Empty`, `Leaf`, or `Node` and must be matched for any of them respectively to deal with all cases.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] In case of `Node`, the pattern extracts the subtrees `l` and `r` for further processing.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data types are highly suited to implementing abstract syntax.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] An element of such a data type would have a form such as `Mult (Add (Number 4) (Minus (Number 0) (Number 1))) (Number 2)`.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Writing an evaluation function for this language is a simple exercise; however, more complex transformations also become feasible.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] For example, an optimization pass in a compiler might be written as a function taking an abstract expression as input and returning an optimized form.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data types are used to represent values that can be one of several *types of things*.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Each type of thing is associated with an identifier called a *constructor*, which can be considered a tag for that kind of data.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Each constructor can carry with it a different type of data.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] For example, considering the binary `Tree` example shown above, a constructor could carry no data (e.g., `Empty`), or one piece of data (e.g., `Leaf` has one Int value), or multiple pieces of data (e.g., `Node` has one `Int` value and two `Tree` values).
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] To do something with a value of this `Tree` algebraic data type, it is *deconstructed* using a process called pattern matching.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] This involves matching the data with a series of *patterns*.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The example function `depth` above pattern-matches its argument with three patterns.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] When the function is called, it finds the first pattern that matches its argument, performs any variable bindings that are found in the pattern, and evaluates the expression corresponding to the pattern.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Each pattern above has a form that resembles the structure of some possible value of this datatype.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The first pattern simply matches values of the constructor `Empty`.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The second pattern matches values of the constructor `Leaf`.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Patterns are recursive, so then the data that is associated with that constructor is matched with the pattern "n".
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] In this case, a lowercase identifier represents a pattern that matches any value, which then is bound to a variable of that name — in this case, a variable "`n`" is bound to the integer value stored in the data type — to be used in the expression to evaluate.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Recursive patterns several layers deep are used for example in balancing red–black trees, which involve cases that require looking at colors several layers deep.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The advantages of algebraic data types can be highlighted by comparison of the above pseudocode with a pattern matching equivalent.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] In the pseudocode example above, programmer diligence is required to not access field2 when the constructor is a `Leaf`.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The type system would have difficulties assigning a static type in a safe way for traditional record data structures.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] However, in pattern matching such problems are not faced.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The type of each extracted value is based on the types declared by the relevant constructor.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The number of values that can be extracted is known based on the constructor.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Secondly, in pattern matching, the compiler performs exhaustiveness checking to ensure all cases are handled.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] If one of the cases of the *depth* function above were missing, the compiler would issue a warning.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Exhaustiveness checking may seem easy for simple patterns, but with many complex recursive patterns, the task soon becomes difficult for the average human (or compiler, if it must check arbitrary nested if-else constructs).
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Similarly, there may be patterns which never match (i.e., are already covered by prior patterns).
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The compiler can also check and issue warnings for these, as they may indicate an error in reasoning.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data type pattern matching should not be confused with regular expression string pattern matching.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The purpose of both is similar (to extract parts from a piece of data matching certain constraints) however, the implementation is very different.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Pattern matching on algebraic data types matches on the structural properties of an object rather than on the character sequence of strings.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] A general algebraic data type is a possibly recursive sum type of product types.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Each constructor tags a product type to separate it from others, or if there is only one constructor, the data type is a product type.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] Further, the parameter types of a constructor are the factors of the product type.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] A parameterless constructor corresponds to the empty product.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] If a datatype is recursive, the entire sum of products is wrapped in a recursive type, and each constructor also rolls the datatype into the recursive type.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] is represented in type theory as $\lambda \alpha .\mu \beta .1+\alpha \times \beta$ with constructors $\mathrm {nil} _{\alpha }=\mathrm {roll} \ (\mathrm {inl} \ \langle \rangle )$ and $\mathrm {cons} _{\alpha }\ x\ l=\mathrm {roll} \ (\mathrm {inr} \ \langle x,l\rangle )$ .
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The Haskell List datatype can also be represented in type theory in a slightly different form, thus: $\mu \phi .\lambda \alpha .1+\alpha \times \phi \ \alpha$ .
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] (Note how the $\mu$ and $\lambda$ constructs are reversed relative to the original.) The original formation specified a type function whose body was a recursive type.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] The revised version specifies a recursive function on types.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] (The type variable $\phi$ is used to suggest a function rather than a *base type* like $\beta$ , since $\phi$ is like a Greek *f*.) The function must also now be applied $\phi$ to its argument type $\alpha$ in the body of the type.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] For the purposes of the List example, these two formulations are not significantly different; but the second form allows expressing so-called nested data types, i.e., those where the recursive type differs parametrically from the original.
[src:purescript/algebraic-data-type] In set theory the equivalent of a sum type is a disjoint union, a set whose elements are pairs consisting of a tag (equivalent to a constructor) and an object of a type corresponding to the tag (equivalent to the constructor arguments).
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] This repository contains a community fork of *PureScript by Example* by Phil Freeman, also known as “the PureScript book”.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] This version differs from the original in that it has been updated so that the code and exercises work with up-to-date versions of the compiler, libraries, and tools.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] Some chapters have also been rewritten to showcase the latest features of the PureScript ecosystem.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] If you enjoyed the book or found it useful, please consider buying a copy of the original on Leanpub.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] This book is being continuously updated as the language evolves, so please report any issues you discover with the material.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] We appreciate any feedback you have to share, even if it’s as simple as pointing out a confusing section that we could make more beginner-friendly.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] Unit tests are also being added to each chapter so you can check if your answers to the exercises are correct.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] PureScript is a small, strongly, statically typed programming language with expressive types, written in and inspired by Haskell, and compiling to Javascript.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] Functional programming in JavaScript has seen quite a lot of popularity recently, but large-scale application development is hindered by the lack of a disciplined environment in which to write code.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] PureScript aims to solve that problem by bringing the power of strongly-typed functional programming to the world of JavaScript development.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] This book will show you how to get started with the PureScript programming language, from the basics (setting up a development environment) to the advanced.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] Each chapter will be motivated by a particular problem, and in the course of solving that problem, new functional programming tools and techniques will be introduced.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] The text of this book is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/deed.en_US.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] Some text is derived from the PureScript Documentation Repo, which uses the same license, and is copyright various contributors.
[src:purescript/book-purescript-org] The exercises are licensed under the MIT license.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] In computer science, **purely functional programming** usually designates a programming paradigm—a style of building the structure and elements of computer programs—that treats all computation as the evaluation of mathematical functions.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] This style handles state changes without losing the referential transparency of the program expressions.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programming consists of ensuring that functions, inside the functional paradigm, will only depend on their arguments, regardless of any global or local state.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] A pure functional subroutine only has visibility of changes of state represented by state variables included in its scope.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] The exact difference between pure and impure functional programming is a matter of controversy.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Sabry's proposed definition of purity is that all common evaluation strategies (call-by-name, call-by-value, and call-by-need) produce the same result, ignoring strategies that error or diverge.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] A program is usually said to be functional when it uses some concepts of functional programming, such as first-class functions and higher-order functions.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] However, a first-class function need not be purely functional, as it may use techniques from the imperative paradigm, such as arrays or input/output methods that use mutable cells, which update their state as side effects.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] In fact, the earliest programming languages cited as being functional, IPL and Lisp, are both "impure" functional languages by Sabry's definition.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Each evaluation strategy which ends on a purely functional program returns the same result.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] In particular, it ensures that the programmer does not have to consider in which order programs are evaluated, since eager evaluation will return the same result as lazy evaluation.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] However, it is still possible that an eager evaluation may not terminate while the lazy evaluation of the same program halts.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] An advantage of this is that lazy evaluation can be implemented much more easily; as all expressions will return the same result at any moment (regardless of program state), their evaluation can be delayed as much as necessary.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] In a purely functional language, the only dependencies between computations are data dependencies, and computations are deterministic.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, to program in parallel, the programmer need only specify the pieces that should be computed in parallel, and the runtime can handle all other details such as distributing tasks to processors, managing synchronization and communication, and collecting garbage in parallel.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] This style of programming avoids common issues such as race conditions and deadlocks, but has less control than an imperative language.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] To ensure a speedup, the granularity of tasks must be carefully chosen to be neither too big nor too small.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] In theory, it is possible to use runtime profiling and compile-time analysis to judge whether introducing parallelism will speed up the program, and thus automatically parallelize purely functional programs.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] In practice, this has not been terribly successful, and fully automatic parallelization is not practical.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are persistent.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Persistency is required for functional programming; without it, the same computation could return different results.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Functional programming may use persistent non-purely functional data structures, while those data structures may not be used in purely functional programs.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way than their imperative counterparts.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] For example, array with constant-time access and update is a basic component of most imperative languages and many imperative data-structures, such as hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by map or random access list, which admits purely functional implementation, but the access and update time is logarithmic.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, purely functional data structures can be used in languages which are non-functional, but they may not be the most efficient tool available, especially if persistency is not required.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] In general, conversion of an imperative program to a purely functional one also requires ensuring that the formerly-mutable structures are now explicitly returned from functions that update them, a program structure called store-passing style.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] A purely functional language is a language which only admits purely functional programming.
[src:purescript/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programs can however be written in languages which are not purely functional.
[src:purescript/purescript] PureScript was initially designed by Phil Freeman in 2013.
[src:purescript/purescript] He began work on it because he was unsatisfied by other attempts to transpile Haskell to JavaScript (e.g., using Fay, Haste, or GHCJS).
[src:purescript/purescript] Since then it has been adopted by the community and is developed on GitHub.
[src:purescript/purescript] Further community-developed core tools include the dedicated build tool *Pulp*, the documentation directory *Pursuit*, and the package manager *Spago*.
[src:purescript/purescript] PureScript features strict evaluation, persistent data structures, and type inference.
[src:purescript/purescript] Its data type system shares many features with those of similar functional languages like Haskell: algebraic data types and pattern matching, higher kinded types, type classes, functional dependencies, and higher-rank polymorphism.
[src:purescript/purescript] Its type system adds support for row polymorphism and extensible records, but does not support some of the more advanced features of Haskell such as the generalized algebraic data type (GADT) and the type family.
[src:purescript/purescript] The PureScript transpilers attempt to produce readable code, where possible.
[src:purescript/purescript] Through a simple foreign function interface (FFI), it also allows code reuse of extant source code in JavaScript, C++11, and Go, usually as an intermediate representation.
[src:purescript/purescript] PureScript supports incremental compilation, and the transpiler to JavaScript distribution supports building source-code editor plug-ins for iterative development.
[src:purescript/purescript] Editor plug-ins exist for many popular text editors, including Vim, Emacs, Sublime Text, Atom and Visual Studio Code.
[src:purescript/purescript] PureScript supports type-driven development via its typed holes feature, in which a program can be constructed with missing subexpressions.
[src:purescript/purescript] The JavaScript transpiler will subsequently attempt to infer the types of the missing subexpressions, and report those types to the user.
[src:purescript/purescript] This feature inspired similar work in the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC).
[src:purescript/purescript] Here, the type of the program is inferred and checked by the PureScript transpiler.
[src:purescript/www-purescript-org] Precompiled binaries are available for OSX, Linux, and Windows from the latest release page on GitHub.
[src:purescript/www-purescript-org] You might like to install some of these additional tools and editor plugins.
[src:purescript/www-purescript-org] NPM is recommended for managing JavaScript dependencies in your project.
[src:purescript/www-purescript-org] The Pursuit package database hosts searchable documentation for PureScript packages.
[src:purescript/www-purescript-org] The free PureScript By Example book contains several practical projects for PureScript beginners.
[src:purescript/www-purescript-org] Visit the documentation repository on GitHub, the central place where you can find articles, in-depth learning resources for beginners, and more.
